Up until May 2003, [Paddington](/Paddington_station) was an integral part of the [Virgin CrossCountry](/Virgin_CrossCountry) network, offering services that stretched northwards to England and Scotland, typically via [Oxford](/Oxford_railway_station) and the bustling hub of [Birmingham New Street](/Birmingham_New_Street_railway_station) [71]. From June 2005 until May 2018, [Paddington](/Paddington_station) also served as the terminus for [Heathrow Connect](/Heathrow_Connect) services, a slightly less glamorous but equally functional link to the airport [72] [73].

Until December 2018, [Chiltern Railways](/Chiltern_Railways) operated a rather niche weekday [parliamentary service](/Parliamentary_train) from [South Ruislip](/South_Ruislip_station) and to [High Wycombe](/High_Wycombe_railway_station), meticulously traversing the [Acton–Northolt line](/Acton%E2%80%93Northolt_line) [74] [75]. This service, a relic of railway history, ceased when the Acton-Northolt line itself closed, an inevitable consequence of progress. Interestingly, when its usual London terminus at [Marylebone](/Marylebone_railway_station) was temporarily unavailable, [Chiltern Railways](/Chiltern_Railways) would, with a sense of reluctant necessity, divert its services to [London Paddington](/Paddington_station). Similarly, [Wrexham & Shropshire](/Wrexham_%26_Shropshire) also utilized [Paddington](/Paddington_station) between 2008 and 2011 when their own terminus was closed [76] [77], proving that even the most disparate railway lines occasionally find common ground.

The platforms inside the train shed at London Paddington station. Three of the platforms are occupied by First Great Western [High Speed Trains](/InterCity_125), while another two have Heathrow Express [British Rail Class 332](/British_Rail_Class_332) [Electric Multiple Units](/Electric_multiple_units)

### Accidents and incidents

One might imagine a station as grand as [Paddington](/Paddington_station) would be immune to the mundane misfortunes of everyday operation, but alas, even monumental infrastructure is subject to the whims of fate and human error. On 9 August 1920, a passenger train, perhaps with a touch too much enthusiasm, collided with the buffers, resulting in two unfortunate injuries [78]. The following year, a similar, though perhaps more complex, incident occurred when a passenger train, in the process of being shunted into a platform, rather unexpectedly collided with three luggage vans that were already occupying the line. The outcome was a derailed carriage and a thoroughly wrecked luggage van [79], a rather dramatic display of inefficiency.

On 23 November 1983, a sleeper train, under the command of [Class 50](/British_Rail_Class_50) locomotive 50 041 *Bulwark*, met an unfortunate end, derailing on the approach to [Paddington](/Paddington_station) after exceeding the speed limit through a crossover. Though the consequences could have been far worse, three of the seventy passengers sustained injuries [80] [81], a stark reminder of the unforgiving nature of physics.

The station, sadly, has also been a target of more sinister forces. On 18 February 1991, [Paddington](/Paddington_station) was subjected to a [bombing](/Bombings_of_Paddington_and_Victoria_stations) by the [Provisional IRA](/Provisional_Irish_Republican_Army), an act that inflicted significant damage upon the station's iconic roof. A mere three hours later, [London Victoria station](/London_Victoria_station) suffered an even more serious and devastating attack [82], highlighting a dark chapter in London's history.

However, the most tragic and widely remembered incident at [Paddington](/Paddington_station) remains the [Ladbroke Grove rail crash](/Ladbroke_Grove_rail_crash), also grimly referred to as the Paddington rail crash. On 5 October 1999, a Thames Train stopping service, departing from [Paddington](/Paddington_station) en route to [Bedwyn](/Bedwyn_railway_station), catastrophically [passed a red signal](/Signal_passed_at_danger), resulting in a head-on collision with a Great Western express traveling in the opposite direction. The devastating impact claimed the lives of both train drivers and 29 passengers, while a further 400 individuals sustained injuries [83] [84], a profound and somber reminder of the critical importance of safety protocols.

More recently, on 25 May 2014, the middle coach of an empty stock [Class 360](/British_Rail_Class_360) [electric multiple unit](/Electric_multiple_unit) 360 205 derailed as it entered platform 3. The cause was attributed to maintenance errors [85], a testament to the fact that even seemingly minor oversights can lead to significant disruptions. On 16 June 2016, a [Class 165](/British_Rail_Class_165) [diesel multiple unit](/Diesel_multiple_unit) 165 124, in a moment of apparent lapse, passed a signal at danger and subsequently derailed in a siding. This incident, while less catastrophic, caused considerable disruption to services and inflicted damage upon the infrastructure [86].

On 13 July 2017, an [electrical fire](/Electrical_fire) originating in an intake room led to the evacuation of approximately 2,000 people [87], demonstrating that even the unseen, underlying systems can pose a significant threat. Finally, on 20 August 2017, a [Class 43](/British_Rail_Class_43_(HST)), specifically 43188, experienced a derailment during its departure from Platform 2, while forming the rear power car of the 11:57 service bound for [Penzance](/Penzance_railway_station) [88], proving that even the most routine journeys are not entirely without their potential for unexpected drama.

### London Underground stations

Main articles: [Paddington tube station (Bakerloo, Circle and District lines)](/Paddington_tube_station_(Bakerloo,_Circle_and_District_lines)) and [Paddington tube station (Circle and Hammersmith & City lines)](/Paddington_tube_station_(Circle_and_Hammersmith_%26_City_lines))

The [Great Western Railway](/Great_Western_Railway) (GWR) was acutely aware of [Paddington](/Paddington_station)'s geographical isolation, situated as it was a considerable distance from the bustling heart of central London. Recognizing this strategic disadvantage, in 1854, the GWR made a rather substantial donation of £175,000 (an amount equivalent to approximately £20,748,000 in 2023, for those who appreciate the relentless march of inflation) to the [North Metropolitan Railway](/Metropolitan_Railway). This generous, yet pragmatic, investment was made with the explicit goal of ensuring that [Paddington](/Paddington_station) would be seamlessly linked to the City [26]. Consequently, when the [Metropolitan Railway](/Metropolitan_Railway) officially opened on 1 January 1863, [Paddington](/Paddington_station) proudly served as its original western terminus, marking a pivotal moment in the history of underground transport [26].

A subsequent extension of the [Metropolitan Railway](/Metropolitan_Railway) further enhanced [Paddington](/Paddington_station)'s connectivity, providing a vital link to the areas south of the River Thames. This extension commenced operations on 1 October 1868, branching from Praed Street Junction and incorporating a new, dedicated [station at Paddington, strategically located on Praed Street](/Paddington_tube_station_(Bakerloo,_Circle_and_District_lines)), which then extended to [Gloucester Road](/Gloucester_Road_tube_station) [89]. In a further layering of subterranean networks, an extension of the [Baker Street and Waterloo Railway](/Baker_Street_and_Waterloo_Railway) to [Paddington](/Paddington_station) opened on 1 December 1913, establishing a crucial connection to the Metropolitan Railway's established Praed Street station [90].

Due to this rather convoluted history of various independent railway developments, [Paddington](/Paddington_station) is now served by four distinct [London Underground](/London_Underground) lines, accessible through two entirely separate stations. The first, a combined [sub-surface and deep-level station](/Paddington_tube_station_(Bakerloo,_Circle_and_District_lines)), is located on Praed Street, to the south of the main line station, and caters to the [Bakerloo](/Bakerloo_line), [Circle](/Circle_line_(London_Underground)), and [District](/District_line) lines. The second, a dedicated [sub-surface station](/Paddington_tube_station_(Circle_and_Hammersmith_%26_City_lines)), offers access from [Paddington Basin](/Paddington_Basin) to the north, serving the [Circle](/Circle_line_(London_Underground)) and [Hammersmith & City](/Hammersmith_%26_City_line) lines. A rather peculiar quirk of the system is that [Circle line](/Circle_line_(London_Underground)) services, in their circular (or rather, spiral) route, pass through *both* of these sub-surface stations. However, despite being depicted as a single, unified entity on the iconic [London Underground map](/Tube_map), these two stations are, in fact, not directly linked [91] [92] [93], a detail that often catches the unwary traveler by surprise.

For those willing to stretch their legs, [Lancaster Gate](/Lancaster_Gate_tube_station) Underground station on the [Central line](/Central_line_(London_Underground)) and [Marylebone](/Marylebone_station) mainline station are both comfortably within walking distance. Conveniently, out-of-station interchanges to these stations are permitted at no additional cost, provided they are made within a specified timeframe [2], a small concession to the complexities of urban navigation.

